<li style="position: fixed; bottom:100px; right:100px; background: transparent; z-index:999; height: 98px; padding: 5px; border-radius: 5px;">{{Collapse|num=999|initial=<div class="t-audio-toggle-1">'''Toggle Music'''|final=<span style="opacity:0;">.</span>|body=<span style="opacity:0;"></span></div>}}</li>


<center>
Nobody knows what it truly is, but the Poltergeist has no need to answer why, how or where it exists. That is too irrelevant. The Poltergeist is bored. It wants a game to play. But what game is there to play in the Backrooms? At least, one that is fun and doesn't result in your immediate death? Well, none really, but one can always improvise.


That is what the Poltergeist thinks.


The Poltergeist isn't a physical entity, it is a... psychological entity. While not solid or bound to a strict form, it is created out of the collective curiosity, wonder, and sense of mystery shared by all wanderers of the Backrooms. And thus, depending on the intensity of these emotions, the Poltergeist can be calm, hostile, benevolent, and many other infinite possibilities.
{{Background|file=Void.png}}

However, one trait is consistent. It is bored. It wants to play and satisfy this boredom by any means possible. The Poltergeist is a deity, however. It acts like a hivemind; however, each lifeform has their own version of the Poltergeist. And while the type of Poltergeist they have is defined ever since birth, even before entering the Backrooms, it doesn't mean the Poltergeist is subject to changing behaviors over time.
</center>
{{Collapse|num=3|initial=<center>You may find it cute, odd, or terrifying. Your own, personal little trickster.</center>|final=<center>You may find it cute, odd, or terrifying. Your own, personal little trickster.</center>|body=<br>

<center><span style="font-size:50px;font-family: 'PLAYFUL RUNWAY';"><span style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,white,#494bd6); -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent;text-shadow: 0 0 30px grey, 0 0 30px #494bd6, 0 0 40px #494bd6;">The Poltergeist</span></span></center>
[[File:Spinchair.gif|center|link= ]]
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{User:PayourTAXES769/Polterclass}}
{{Blurimage|file=Poltergeist.png|caption=A thermogram photographing the "manifestation" of a common Poltergeist.}}
{{Blurbackground|file=Plasmabg.gif}}
'''The Poltergeist''' is an egregoric, anomalous entity species formed from the curiosity and wonder of lifeforms. As it is egregoric, it isn't bound to a specific form; rather, '''the Poltergeist''' manifests by using the consciousness of other creatures as a conduit into the physical world. While many forms have been observed, it is most commonly identified as an invisible plasma capable of interacting with and possessing objects, appliances, technology, and, on rare occasions, even other entities.

'''The Poltergeist''' isn't one singular entity, as it has been documented that each wanderer seems to have their own '''Poltergeist''', each with different personalities, behaviors and intentions. However, extensive research indicates that despite this, all '''Poltergeist''' are tied to a singular deity that acts as a hivemind across all '''Poltergeists'''. This deity is mostly theorized to likely reside in the [[Achospic Plane]] as the single unified thoughtform of all curiosity. As it is entirely composed of psychic energy<ref>Psychic energy is what makes up the Achospic Plane. Anything produced by or within the Achospic Plane is composed entirely of psychic energy. Psychic energy is first manifested in the Backrooms, where it travels through The Void and into the Achospic Plane, joining the ring. Some theories suggest it also originates from baseline reality, going through the same process to join the Achospic Plane.</ref>, any psychic energy within this deity that becomes unstable is ejected into the Backrooms as psychic noise<ref>When destabilized or otherwise removed from The Achospic Plane, psychic energy becomes psychic noise. Psychic noise latches onto the emotions and thoughts it is created out of to produce various features of the Backrooms.</ref>, allowing '''Poltergeists''' to fully form. As a result, '''Poltergeists''' can range from being mostly calm, neutral, or aggressive, and '''Poltergeists''' from different lifeforms are capable of interacting and communicating with each other.

They appear to be personally tied to a wanderer's own personality, memories, and consciousness. It is generally believed these entities are formed ever since the wanderer is born; however, the intense feelings of liminality, curiosity, and the 'unknown' found exclusively in the Backrooms are what trigger the '''Poltergeists''' to finally take shape. '''Poltergeists''' remain mysterious; despite these theories, there are multiple common cases of wanderers living their whole lives without ever meeting their own '''Poltergeist'''. While it is rare to find your own '''Poltergeist''', it is much more common to experience other lifeforms' '''Poltergeists''' interacting with the world or causing spatial distortions.
==Biology and Behaviors==
{{Blurimage|file=polterpc.jpg|caption=An instance of a Poltergeist possessing a computer monitor.}}
'''Poltergeists''', as mentioned before, have no strict or consistent form, as they are manifestations of the mind. However, they are most commonly observed to take the form of small, invisible plasma bodies, spanning over 40.64 centimeters (or 1 foot 4 inches) tall. Despite being extremely hot, it is shown that '''Poltergeists''' purposefully regulate their temperatures around other creatures or wanderers, and this trait appears to be constant to all '''Poltergeists'''.

'''Poltergeists''' are born as near-infinitesimal amounts of psychic noise in a wanderer that slowly develops as emotions of curiosity. It is currently unknown ''when'' they form, but they only manifest fully once the wanderer enters the Backrooms.

Despite being incorporeal, '''Poltergeists''' are capable of interacting with other objects. They may push items, carry objects around, or purposefully make thuds or noises on purpose to scare wanderers. A universal trait that seems to be identified with all specimens is that they appear to have a mischievous or playful personality, intentionally trying to scare other wanderers, imitating noises from entities such as [[Entity 8|Hounds]] or [[Entity 3|Smilers]], or deliberately creaking doors and replicating the sound of breathing or footsteps. They may throw items spontaneously and, in rare cases, possess dolls, technological appliances, and even other entities. However, these may also work in the wanderer's favor, as '''Poltergeists''' may naturally use these abilities to repel other hostile entities. '''Poltergeists''' are able to lift any object, regardless of its size or weight.

'''Poltergeists''' are functionally immortal, as they only cease to exist when the wanderer they're tied to dies. This creates a natural archetype where '''Poltergeists''' may actively try to keep the wanderer safe from lethal risks by leading them to safe level entrances, helping find resources, and distracting other entities while maintaining a playful yet grounded personality, and more mischievous or even hostile ones may try to sabotage the wanderer, alert entities, steal resources, set up traps, or lead the wanderer into dead ends, effectively being "suicidal".
{{Blurimage|file=poltering.png|caption=A Poltergeist seen levitating objects and appliances.}}
The intentions and moralities of '''Poltergeists''' are tied to the intensity, aggressiveness, and drive of the lifeform's curiosity. For example, if the curiosity stems from innocence and unfiltered wonder, '''Poltergeists''' have a higher chance of being docile and friendly, while curiosity formed from fear, negative intentions, and greed has a higher chance of hosting aggressive '''Poltergeists'''. 

Finally, '''Poltergeists''' can develop deep connections with other wanderers. Wanderers that have greatly tapped into their curiosity and achieved peace of mind are reported to be able to communicate with their '''Poltergeists''' telepathically. This, combined with '''Poltergeists'''' high potential as resource finders, intel providers, and disruptors, makes wanderers with this ability highly effective and capable of achieving tremendous feats. However, this is incredibly rare, as the high influx of negative emotions in the Backrooms makes it difficult to create these types of connections without resulting in hostile or erratic '''Poltergeists'''.
==History and Discovery==
{{Blurimage|file=oldpolter.gif|caption=One of the oldest sightings of a Poltergeist, location unknown.}}
'''Poltergeists''' are believed to have existed since the first arrival of humans in '''the Backroooms'''. However, for a long time, it was believed that the phenomena and anomalies caused by '''Poltergeists''' were merely common Backrooms anomalies rather than entities. This changed, however, as an influx of wanderers reported talking with 'little ghosts' whenever they felt alone. Multiple research studies, specifically through the use of thermograms, allowed researchers to notice bodies of plasma and heat seemed to move on their own, move objects around, and emit noises while being invisible to the naked eye. This resulted in said entities being called 'Poltergeists', known in Frontrooms mythology as a ghost or paranormal entity that causes physical disturbances.

Sooner on, around the 1970s, extensive research saw that specific '''Poltergeists''' appeared to fade away whenever a specific wanderer died, leading to further documentation and hypothesis that these entities were somehow tied to these wanderers, and finally in the 2000s, it was concluded '''Poltergeists''' can be manifested from almost any lifeform as long as said organism is intelligent enough to process feelings such as curiosity that brought these entities to life through the mind, functioning very similar to [[Phenomenon 9]]. However, a clear difference lies. '''Poltergeists''' are egregoric, meaning that despite being tied to one specific wanderer, they require the collective thoughts of multiple people to ultimately manifest, which is why many wanderers would live their lives without ever meeting their own. This was further proved as '''Poltergeists''' have recently been discovered to be more common in groups of people or populated places. Additionally, unlike standard Tulpas, '''Poltergeists''' are not just thoughtforms, they also are manifestations of a lifeform's curiosity in general. As such, despite the similarity between these two phenomena, the formation of '''Poltergeists''' is more nuanced.
{{Blurimage|file=WtfPolter.webp|caption=One of the most iconic photographs of a Poltergeist, seen lifting a chair in [[Level 46]]. Presumably photographed by [[Entity 1|The Cameraman]].}}
Even after multiple investigation and documentation done on'''Poltergeists''', they remain ambiguous. Recent studies made by investigating the behavior of '''Poltergeists''' suggest they all may be connected to a singular hivemind. This is indicated by the fact all '''Poltergeists''' display a playful or mischievous personality, regardless of their hostility level. Additionally, '''Poltergeists''' were reported to be able to interact with each other, and findings revealed that these entities seem to achieve a state of perfect synchronization with each other, further cementing that all '''Poltergeists''' are all connected to a singular consciousness.

Currently, '''Poltergeists''', despite their abundance, have continued to remain mostly anonymous to other wanderers, usually being seen as daily "troublemakers" that cause phenomena and spatial distortions. This doesn't mean '''Poltergeists''' can't be dangerous, as there are multiple cases of '''Poltergeists''' indirectly causing the deaths of many wanderers by bringing other entities' attention to them or even throwing objects at wanderers. As such, in places with a high population density of '''Poltergeists''', these entities usually remain either a common 'pest', or a dangerous, unpredictable entity. 
